Here's what you need to know: Symptoms: The characteristic symptom is the presence of dark green rings or C-shaped markings on the fruit. Leaves may exhibit a mottled or mosaic pattern, distortion, and a ruffled appearance. Transmission: The virus is primarily spread by aphids, which can easily transmit transmit it between plants. Impact: PRSV can significantly reduce fruit quality and yield, and can even lead to plant death. Control: • Prevention: Use disease-free seedlings, raise seedlings…

reviews.review_text: All bad. 1st fruit was green, so we left it to ripen. Instead of smelling sweet, the scent was fermented like beer. We thought we did something wrong, so we bought a second. This time we also bought an apple and paper bags, just in case they sent us another unripe papaya. The new one was yellow and had practically no scent. It was soft, perhaps too soft. The skin was able to be slid off of some parts. It had no mold or mildew, but smelled strongly of something distinctly chemical. Knowing that some people like papaya and others don't, I tried it. Tasted like I was chewing latex gloves. I'm going to have to take lessons on this fruit. In the meantime, I won't order when they don't send them closer to their use by date. If I order Papaya today, I want to enjoy it this week, not get them in varying stages of ripeness and/or decay.
